            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is Human Life Value?</h2>
              <p>
                Human Life Value (HLV) is an estimate of the economic value of
                your life to your dependents. It answers the question:
                <strong
                  >If I died today, how much capital would my family need to
                  replace my future earnings until retirement?</strong
                >
              </p>
              <p>
                Insurers and financial planners use HLV to guide life insurance
                recommendations. Instead of using a simple income multiple (like
                “10× income”), HLV discounts each future year’s income back to
                today, taking into account taxes, personal spending, income
                growth, inflation and investment returns.
              </p>

              <h2>Formula used by this Human Life Value calculator</h2>
              <p>
                This tool uses a
                <strong>growing annuity present value</strong> model for your
                after-tax, after-expense income.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Step 1 – Net income available to dependents (today):
                </p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( I_0 \) = current annual gross income</li>
                  <li>\( t \) = effective tax rate</li>
                  <li>\( p \) = personal expense rate (self-use)</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Then net income for dependents today is:</p>
                <p>\( \text{Net}_0 = I_0 \times (1 - t) \times (1 - p) \)</p>
                <p class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1">
                  Step 2 – Present value of growing income stream:
                </p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( g \) = expected annual income growth rate</li>
                  <li>\( i \) = long-term inflation rate</li>
                  <li>\( d \) = expected nominal investment return</li>
                  <li>
                    \( r = \frac{1 + d}{1 + i} - 1 \) = real discount rate
                  </li>
                  <li>\( n \) = years to retirement</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  Human Life Value (HLV) is the present value of a growing
                  annuity:
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{HLV} = \text{Net}_0 \times \dfrac{1 - \left(\dfrac{1
                  + g}{1 + r}\right)^n}{r - g} \)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-600">
                  If \( r \) is very close to \( g \), the calculator safely
                  switches to a year‑by‑year summation to avoid numerical
                  instability.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Suggested life insurance coverage</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator also shows a
                <strong>suggested coverage amount</strong>:
              </p>
              <p>
                \( \text{Suggested coverage} = \max(0,\ \text{HLV} -
                \text{Existing assets for dependents}) \)
              </p>
              <p>
                This is a starting point. You may adjust it for debts,
                children’s education goals, spouse’s income, and other
                resources.
              </p>

              <h2>How to use the Human Life Value calculator effectively</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong
                    >Enter realistic income and growth assumptions.</strong
                  >
                  Avoid overly optimistic growth rates; 2–4% above inflation is
                  common for many careers.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong
                    >Use your effective tax rate, not your top marginal
                    bracket.</strong
                  >
                  Look at last year’s tax return: total tax ÷ taxable income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Be honest about personal expenses.</strong> If you
                  spend 40% of your income on yourself, only 60% is really
                  supporting dependents.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choose a conservative discount rate.</strong> Many
                  planners use 3–5% real (after inflation) for long-term
                  planning.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong
                    >Subtract assets already earmarked for your family.</strong
                  >
                  This avoids double-counting savings and investments.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Human Life Value vs. other approaches</h2>
              <h3>Income multiple method</h3>
              <p>
                A common rule of thumb is to buy life insurance equal to 10–15×
                your annual income. This is simple but ignores taxes, inflation,
                investment returns and your specific retirement horizon.
              </p>
              <p>HLV is more precise because it:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Models income year by year until retirement.</li>
                <li>Adjusts for income growth and inflation.</li>
                <li>Discounts future cash flows to today’s dollars.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Needs-based method</h3>
              <p>
                A needs-based approach starts from specific goals: mortgage
                payoff, children’s college, survivor income, etc. HLV is
                complementary: it focuses on
                <strong>income replacement</strong> rather than specific
                spending targets.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and professional advice</h2>
              <p>
                No calculator can capture every nuance of your financial life.
                Human Life Value is a helpful benchmark, not a verdict.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  It assumes continuous employment until the retirement age you
                  choose.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does not model career breaks, major promotions, or business
                  exits.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Tax rates, inflation and investment returns can change over
                  time.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For large coverage decisions or complex situations (business
                owners, multiple dependents, cross-border tax issues), consider
                reviewing these results with a qualified financial planner or
                insurance professional.
              </p>
            </section>

            <section class="prose mt-8" id="faq">
              <h2>Frequently asked questions about Human Life Value</h2>

              <h3>Is Human Life Value the same as what my life is “worth”?</h3>
              <p>
                No. Human Life Value is
                <strong>only an economic measure</strong> of your future
                earnings for your dependents. It does not attempt to measure
                your intrinsic worth as a person, your relationships, or
                non-financial contributions.
              </p>

              <h3>Why does the discount rate matter so much?</h3>
              <p>
                The discount rate reflects the return your family could
                reasonably earn by investing a lump sum today. A higher discount
                rate means a lower present value of future income (and thus
                lower HLV), and vice versa. Using an unrealistically high rate
                can understate your insurance needs.
              </p>

              <h3>What if I plan to work past traditional retirement age?</h3>
              <p>
                Simply set your planned retirement age higher (for example, 70
                instead of 65). The calculator will include those extra earning
                years in the HLV calculation.
              </p>

